`let` and `const` are preferred in modern JS for scoping and predictability.

Example:
```javascript
var x = 1;
let y = 2;
const z = 3;
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/let

It improves performance by reducing the number of event listeners.

Example:
```javascript
document.getElementById('list').addEventListener('click', function(e) {
  if (e.target && e.target.nodeName === 'LI') {
    console.log('Item clicked:', e.target.textContent);
  }
});
```

 Reference: https://javascript.info/event-delegation

Synchronous code blocks further execution until the current operation completes. Asynchronous code uses mechanisms like callbacks, promises, and async/await to allow non-blocking behavior.

Example:
```javascript
console.log('Start');
setTimeout(() => console.log('Async!'), 1000);
console.log('End');
// Output: Start, End, Async!
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/JavaScript/Asynchronous

A Promise is an object representing the eventual completion or failure of an asynchronous operation.

Example:
```javascript
let promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => resolve('Done!'), 1000);
});
promise.then(result => console.log(result));
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Promise

JavaScript is single-threaded. The event loop allows non-blocking operations by managing a queue of callback functions.

Example:
```javascript
console.log('Start');
setTimeout(() => console.log('Callback'), 0);
console.log('End');
// Output: Start, End, Callback
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/EventLoop

`call()` and `apply()` immediately invoke the function, while `bind()` returns a new function with bound context.

Example:
```javascript
function greet(greeting) {
  console.log(`${greeting}, ${this.name}`);
}
const person = { name: 'Alice' };
greet.call(person, 'Hello');
greet.apply(person, ['Hi']);
const boundGreet = greet.bind(person);
boundGreet('Hey');
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Function

Callbacks are used for asynchronous operations or customizing behavior.

Example:
```javascript
function greet(name, callback) {
  console.log('Hello, ' + name);
  callback();
}
greet('Alice', function() {
  console.log('This is a callback.');
});
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Callback_function

IIFEs are used to create a new scope and avoid polluting the global namespace.

Example:
```javascript
(function() {
  console.log('IIFE executed');
})();
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/IIFE

`map` returns a new array; `forEach` does not return anything.

Example:
```javascript
const arr = [1, 2, 3];
arr.forEach(x => console.log(x));
const doubled = arr.map(x => x * 2);
console.log(doubled); // [2, 4, 6]
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array

`addEventListener` allows multiple event handlers for the same event and element, and provides better control over event handling.

Example:
```javascript
document.getElementById('btn').addEventListener('click', function() {
  alert('Button clicked!');
});
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/EventTarget/addEventListener

`var` is function-scoped and hoisted. `let` and `const` are block-scoped. `const` is immutable.

Example:
```javascript
var x = 1;
let y = 2;
const z = 3;
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/let

Closures allow for data privacy and maintaining state in asynchronous programming.

Example:
```javascript
function outer() {
  let counter = 0;
  return function inner() {
    counter++;
    return counter;
  }
}
const count = outer();
console.log(count()); // 1
console.log(count()); // 2
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Closures

It allows a single event handler on a parent element to manage events from multiple child elements.

Example:
```javascript
document.getElementById('parent').addEventListener('click', function(e) {
  if (e.target.matches('.child')) {
    console.log('Child clicked');
  }
});
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/JavaScript/Building_blocks/Events
